equation_narrative.headline: Aromatic core position resolved through hydrophobic contacts and late F/Y discrimination
equation_narrative.story: Position 45 in ubiquitin sits in a hydrophobic core environment, surrounded by 6 structural contacts that establish strong aromatic character through layers 1-23. The representation remains broadly hydrophobic through the perception phase, with the logit lens reflecting aliphatic residues (L, V) that share the buried, nonpolar context. The decision crystallizes at L25-27 when aromatic-specific prediction channels activate, discriminating between phenylalanine and tyrosine. F ultimately wins at L32 through strong MLP support (N32:693, N32:929 each contributing >1.0 projection), while Y peaks earlier at L30 (57.5%) before being suppressed.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a clear hydrophobic core context through structural attention. Six structural contacts provide consistent nonpolar signal, with attention heads at L16 (head 9, +1.96 projection) and L18 reading buried positions. The logit lens reflects this hydrophobic character through aliphatic residues: L and V alternate as leaders through L21, reaching 29.4% and 24.5% respectively. Cysteine briefly peaks at L23 (24.9%), likely reflecting the small-residue preference in tightly packed cores. SAE features at early layers encode general hydrophobic context (F1:5480, F9:5728 with 45.7 and 45.7 projections), while mid-layer features (F18:5929 at 21.9 projection) begin encoding aromatic-compatible environments. The representation is consistently hydrophobic-leaning but not yet aromatic-specific.
perception_phase.context_character: Buried hydrophobic core position with 6 structural contacts establishing strong nonpolar character. The local sequence context (QQRLI[F]AGKQL) and structural environment favor large hydrophobic residues, with the representation encoding aromatic-compatible burial rather than specific aromatic identity through L23.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 6 residues within contact distance, read primarily through L16 head 9 (+1.96 projection, 97.9% local attention) and L18 head attention
Co-evolutionary signal: 2 coupled positions provide weak constraint (minimal attention weight)
Hydrophobic encoding: F9:5728 (45.7 proj, attention) and F9:1281 (41.8 proj) establish nonpolar character
Core burial features: F18:5929 (21.9 proj, attention) encodes tightly packed environment compatible with aromatics

decision_phase.summary: The decision phase begins at L24-25 with aromatic-specific features activating. F25:5110 (1.19 projection, MLP) is a strong F-specific prediction channel that drives the initial aromatic commitment. Y dominates L29-30 (peaking at 57.5%), supported by F30:2521 (52.0 proj, MLP). The final F/Y discrimination occurs at L31-32: massive MLP suppression of Y at L29 (N29:3543 erases -2.39) combined with strong F writers at L32 (N32:693 and N32:929 each +1.0) push F to 85.5% by L33.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from hydrophobic representation to aromatic prediction. At L23, the logit lens shows C (24.9%) leading, reflecting small-residue burial. By L25, Y jumps to 24.8% as F25:5110 activates, the first aromatic-specific prediction channel. This is when the representation transitions from 'buried nonpolar position' to 'aromatic residue required here.'

candidates.narrative: F emerges decisively in the late decision phase after trailing Y through L31. The critical support comes from L32 MLP neurons: N32:693 (+1.04 F projection) and N32:929 (+1.03 F projection) provide strong F-specific votes, while N32:2817 erases Y (-1.50 projection toward Q/S). F33 features (F33:2789, F33:5558, F33:8134 with projections >125) represent final F-specific prediction channels. F rises from 34.4% at L29 to 47.2% at L32, overtaking Y in the final lead change.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges at L25 (3.2%), accelerates L29-32, dominant at L33
key_evidence: F25:5110 (MLP, 1.19 proj) — early F-specific prediction channel initiating aromatic commitment
N32:693 (+1.04 F proj) and N32:929 (+1.03 F proj) — decisive late F writers
F33:2789 (MLP, 129.7 proj) — final F prediction channel with extreme specificity

candidates.narrative: Y dominates the mid-decision phase, rising from 3.5% at L23 to 57.5% at L30, supported by F30:2521 (52.0 projection, MLP) and N29:852 (+0.92 Y projection, with 1.52 total Y vote). Y represents the model's initial aromatic solution before F/Y discrimination. The collapse occurs at L29-32: N29:3543 erases -2.39 (voting for S/A instead), and L32 MLP neurons strongly favor F over Y. Y falls from 57.5% at L30 to 14.1% at L33, losing the final competition despite strong mid-phase support.
key_evidence: F30:2521 (MLP, 52.0 proj) — strongest Y prediction channel at peak
N29:852 (+0.92 F proj, +1.52 Y proj) — Y-preferring aromatic writer
N29:3543 (-2.39 F proj) — catastrophic Y eraser voting for S/A, triggering collapse

candidates.narrative: L leads the logit lens through much of the perception phase (layers 3-21), peaking at 29.4% at L21. This reflects the representation's hydrophobic character as the model reads buried aliphatic contacts, not a belief that L is the answer. L is chemically similar to F in hydrophobicity and burial preference, so the intermediate representation projects toward L in the logit lens. L collapses when aromatic-specific features activate at L24-25, falling to 1.7% by L29 as the model commits to aromatic identity.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L3-21 (peaks 29.4% at L21), collapses L24+
key_evidence: Logit lens artifact: L prominence reflects hydrophobic representation, not L prediction
Shares burial and nonpolar character with F, causing early logit-lens correlation
Suppressed by aromatic commitment at L25 when F25:5110 activates

candidates.narrative: C peaks sharply at L23 (24.9%), the highest probability before aromatic commitment. This likely reflects small-residue encoding in the tightly packed core environment — C shares F's burial preference and compact packing. The spike is a representation artifact: the model has encoded 'small residue in buried core' by L23, which projects toward C in the logit lens. C collapses immediately at L24 (to 24.9% → 21.8%) as aromatic-specific prediction channels override the size-based representation.
key_evidence: L23 peak reflects 'small buried residue' representation, not C prediction
Shares compact packing and burial with F but lacks aromatic character
Immediate suppression at L24 when aromatic features activate

turning_points.description: The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. At L23, the representation encodes 'buried hydrophobic core' with C leading (24.9%) as a small-residue artifact. L24-25 sees the first aromatic-specific prediction channels activate: F25:5110 (1.19 projection) drives Y to 24.8%, overtaking C and T. The MLP at L25 contributes +2.29 total toward the answer, marking the shift from context assembly to aromatic commitment. This is when the model transitions from 'what's here' to 'aromatic required.'

Y reaches its peak (57.5% at L30) through strong MLP support from F30:2521 (52.0 projection) and attention features. However, L29 simultaneously contains the seeds of Y's collapse: N29:3543 erases -2.39 from F (voting for S/A), creating instability. The L30 MLP contributes +5.28 total but includes both Y writers (N30:3431 at +1.26 F) and Y erasers (N30:1005 at -0.70), setting up the final F/Y discrimination at L31-32.

The final F/Y discrimination occurs through coordinated MLP action. L32 is decisive: N32:693 (+1.04 F), N32:929 (+1.03 F), and N32:3989 (+1.03 F) strongly favor F, while N32:2817 (-1.50) erases Y by voting for Q/S. Despite the L32 MLP's net negative contribution (-16.24 total), the F-specific neurons dominate the Y-specific ones. F overtakes Y at L32 (47.2% vs 40.8%) and extends to 85.5% at L33 through final prediction channels F33:2789 and F33:5558 (both >129 projection).

deep_dives.caption: N29:3543 erases -2.39 from F (voting for S/A instead), destabilizing Y's lead. Despite Y writers like N29:852 (+0.92 F, +1.52 Y), the net MLP contribution is -12.01, setting up Y's collapse.

deep_dives.caption: N32:693 (+1.04 F), N32:929 (+1.03 F), and N32:3989 (+1.03 F) provide decisive F support, while N32:2817 (-1.50) erases Y. This is where F overtakes Y (47.2% vs 40.8%) in the final lead change.

deep_dives.caption: F33:2789 (129.7 proj, MLP) and F33:5558 (129.5 proj, MLP) are extreme F-specific prediction channels that lock in the final 85.5% confidence. These represent the model's committed F prediction.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts F by assembling a hydrophobic core context through structural contacts (6 neighbors) in layers 1-23, then discriminating between aromatic candidates F and Y in layers 24-33. The decisive evidence comes from L32 MLP neurons (N32:693, N32:929) that strongly favor F over Y, combined with Y-erasing neurons (N32:2817) that destabilize Y's earlier dominance. The representation evolves from 'buried nonpolar' (reflected in early L/V logit-lens leaders) to 'aromatic required' (L25 commitment) to 'F specifically' (L32 discrimination), demonstrating the model's hierarchical refinement from chemical class to specific residue.
